segments.text: my 42nd wedding anniversary happy anniversary thank you it's a slightly cloudy day outside sitting in the living room clint phillips house at 1704 glade and now we're going to stop and be sure that it's working clint before you came here um

give us a brief biographical summary of you where you grew up and went to school and your academic experience before you came to a m okay i was drafted into the army in world war ii and almost immediately became i was in the what was called the asdp program but when i got into
Fort Hayes, Ohio, where I was literally admitted into the Army.
I was asked if I wanted to be an aviation cadet.
I said yes.
I was sent to Jefferson Barracks for pre-training and then on to Marietta College, where I got the equivalent of almost a year's college in five months.
And then went on and did the rest of the service bit.
Came back and went to Baldwin Wallace College in Berea, Ohio.
Managed to get through school working part time.
and started in the summer of 46, finished in the fall of 48, August of 48, and was at Vanderbilt working on a master's September of 48.
Came back a year later and taught two years at Baldwin Wallace, then went back to Vanderbilt to work on my doctorate
which I got, finished the dissertation after I had taken a job, two years after I had taken a job in 1954 at the University of Tennessee.
So in 56 I got the Ph.D. Now this is all in finance?
This is in economics.
I got the degree in economics.
I was in the economics department at Tennessee.
Two years after I got the degree, I started out as an instructor, became an assistant professor the next year, an associate the third, which is kind of phenomenal.
Then I stayed an associate for a while.
But in 58, I moved to Tulane University in New Orleans, where I remained until 1967.
While there, I twice served as an acting dean of a business school.
as associate dean most of the time that I was there when I was an acting dean.
Came here in 67 as a full professor.
By then I was a full professor at Tulane.
Found it to be quite a startling difference.
Do you want me to go into that?
Let me break in at this point.
How did you and A&M become linked up?
What was the process?
I had chaired a seminar for visiting faculty members at Tulane.
Tulane was in the forefront of introducing the computer to the business college environment
In fact, I was one of the first to use a business game for decision-making purposes on an old IBM 1650, which took 55 minutes to process a decision, which would go in a snap of a finger now.
I had this program and George Rice from the management department came from A&M as a participant.
He went back and later I got a letter from here from George saying could I recommend some people that were graduates of our program and I mentioned some and I also said I might be interested.
because I was getting kind of tired of the school situation in New Orleans, which you may know is particularly difficult at that time.
We had our child and both children in private schools because the public schools are so bad.
So anyway, to make a long story short, I came here in 67 as a professor of management.
management.
And let's see, I'm not going to ask any other dollars in this.
What was the beginning salary?
Sixteen fifty.
Sixteen thousand five hundred.
For nine months.
For nine months.
And you... And one of the reasons I was interested in this place is that the AAUP bulletin had listed the five or three or whatever top schools in terms of percentage increases in salary.
And I thought that was interesting.
So I came here making more than I'd been making as a teen at Tulane, which wasn't a lot of money.
I mean, the year before, I think Tom Saving had come at around 40 or 45K, but he was well known.
At that point, organizationally, business was a school or was it yet a college?
It was still a school, and the dean was... Hubert?
Hubert.
Yeah.
So it was a school within the College of Arts and Sciences.
That's correct.
John Pearson was the director.
Who were the key business faculty and administrator leaders at that time?
Well, I suppose George Rice would have been one of them in management.
John Pearson was serving as a business analysis acting head, even though he was a director.
Marketing, oh, I've forgotten his name, but he's still here.
Accounting was a fellow named Jack Coleman.
He left shortly after and became a dean somewhere in California.
Anyway.
What was the reputation of A&M in general business?
Just getting off the ground, really.
It wasn't a college.
It was not accredited by the American Association of Collegiate Schools of Business.
But I saw this place as a
you know, a place whose time had come.
And, you know, in hindsight, I was right.
But so were a lot of people at that time.
I don't take any special... What was, for you and your family, what was your impression of the community when you arrived?
Well, of course, we came from New Orleans, where we had our own waiter at Antoine's, and the same one the business school used all the time.
And so this was a terrible shock.
For Judy, it was fortunate there was a fledgling League of Women Voters group developing, and she got involved in that.
She'd been in the League since the days we were in Knoxville.
She'd been a secretary of the State League in Louisiana.
So she was really into that.
That helped.
And the kids were happy in the school here.
How did you find the quality of the schools, local?
Quite good.
They went to South Knoll over here.
So that was good, but otherwise, you know, when you're used to dining out, it was the Texan, and that was that.
One of the things that kind of wowed me was I was taken over to see the president when I was being interviewed, and so...

Earl Rutter and I talked for about thirty minutes about the Jolly Green Giant of New Orleans the Attorney General there who was involved in the Kennedy assassination business Jim Garrison was his name he was called there the Jolly Green Giant so did Rutter know him or anything no he didn't know him but he was really up on politics of course
And it had happened, the assassination of course in Dallas, and I suppose he knew a whole lot about that.
What was your impression of Rutter based on that conversation?
really, I was not really impressed.
I thought gee whiz, this guy is president of a major university and the kind of people I'd known as presidents before were more academic.
I subsequently became extraordinarily
impressed by what he did and I said so publicly in fact got a nice comment from Mrs.
Rudder Margaret about Oh you're meaning after his passing?

No even while I was still here and got to know really what a role he had played in turning this place in the right direction and of course with Jack Williams coming on after him it was a perfect combination
What about the quality of the students when you first arrived?
Did they make any impression?
I thought the students were reasonably good.
I was not impressed with the graduate students.
But they have since, of course, become...
I remember I had two cases of plagiarism in a master's course.
It just amazed me that they had... One guy had gone all the way through undergraduate school and had never written a paper, which really distressed me.
kind of, it was still a Bush League school in my judgment.
People who had doctorates flouted it.
I found that Bush League at Tulane, we went to great pains to put Mr.
So and So on the door.
Although students might call you Doctor.
Everybody was Mister.
Everybody was Mister.
It was, there was an enormous, Chicago, University of Chicago had an enormous influence on Tulane, in part because so many Chicago PhDs were there.
Anyway, there was a lot that really bothered me about this place.

I fell in with a group that met over in that round circle, rotunda kind of thing in the YMCA building, a lunch bunch, met every Friday or every once a month, I don't know, and we gave little papers, and it was sort of a hatchery.
Did we call that the Brown Baggers?
Yeah, it was called the Brown Baggers, that's what it was.
I wish there was such as that now.
I'd love to be part of one again.
Yeah.
Because that was fun.
I thought it was fun.
Now, all right, did you have, in those first years, did you have much interaction with John Pearson?
Yeah, a good bit, and as a matter of fact, within two years, the end of the second year,
about to enter the third year.
I'm walking across the campus with him, and he says, I've got a terrible problem.
I hired a guy to be head of the finance department, and he called me this noon and said he can't come.
He didn't know that he didn't have a Ph.D.
Guy was getting it at Northwestern.
He looked good on paper, but in any event, didn't come.
He said, will you serve?
His words were, I'm not asking you, I'm telling you, I want you to be the acting head of finance.
So that was how I came to be head of the finance department.
I wasn't even in the department.
That would be 69, fall of 69.
Rutter's last full year.
That's right.
I was in the academic council at the time and sat in those meetings over which he presided.
Describe those meetings.
Do you remember any important topics you all discussed?
I'm trying to remember one.
It had to do with faculty responsibility.

I'm vague about it but it had to do with putting more regulations on faculty to make sure they were coming to the office on time and things like that and Rutter kind of said we expect people to do what they're supposed to be doing but it was kind of an interesting session.
I remember
Another, this probably happened after Rutter had died, but there was a furor or at least a little flame over whether we should tear the old water tower down.
The then department head of Modern Languages, whose name I've forgotten, who retired or
It doesn't ring a bell.
His name starts with D, I think.
He fought for keeping the water tower.
I never thought I'd see somebody from liberal arts, you know, doing that.
Anyway, it went down, and we got a new one.
It was all pretty much...
Describe the department that you took over.
Consisted of three people.
Oh, that's all?

One who had just arrived, one who had been around, Marianne Piotrowski, who had excellent credentials, master's from Sabon and a doctorate from the London School, and then some guy that John had picked up with a master's degree that lasted a year.
I mean, it was pitiful.
And the courses were all descriptive.
A lot of insurance courses taught by
And he was on the city council.
Herschel Burgess?
No, no, he died.
Burgess, Keshner, his wife.
Well, it's easy to look up.
Anyway, he taught all these insurance courses.
Wayne Etter and I became pretty close.
He was my assistant department head, which left only Piotrowski.
who was a real nice guy, but he reached sixty-five in a couple years now, and in those days that was it.
Anyway, well, he threw out all the finance courses, I mean all of the insurance courses, kept one, risk management, and revitalized the whole program.
Yeah, you all were housed office-wise where?
Oh, next to the library in the old, what was the name of it, the veterinary medicine school.

then we spread into the engineering school in fact I had Benson's old office for a while and then the the year well that was a later time when I was acting dean anyway I had to have heart surgery when I was 77 that was six years after I'd
been department head, almost finishing my sixth year.
Alright, let's back up.
Do you remember any personal reaction when you heard that Mr. Rutter was ill or that he had died?
Well, I think there was great concern on campus about, naturally, one wonders about the successor.
I remember John Pearson calling me to tell me who the successor was, and I hadn't even heard of him, General Ludicke, who I think was the ideal guy for the time.
Yes, I agree.
Oh, but there was great sorrow.
I remember going to the service, as I'm sure you do, and LBJ and Lady Bird were there, everybody who was in it.
The Shivers, the Connellys, and Teague and all.
And it was in Jolly Raleigh, yeah, and it was a full house.
Yes, yes.
Impressive.
Now, did you have any interaction with Wayne Hall?
Only when I first came.
I was very impressed with him.
Alright, then with Bill Graff, did you?
Hardly any.
Alright, he followed as chief academic officer.
And, alright, when you first got here, almost all male students.
As I once said to somebody, you walked across the campus propelled on a sea of Howdies.
It was, I found that a little hard to take, hardly any women in the classes, but one saw the signs of its changing, and so I took heart from that.
Alright, then Jack Williams comes.
Did you have any communication with him early on?
Not early on.
I became, along with
a chap in the engineering college advisor to the Black Awareness Committee.
And they were taking actions without we advisors even knowing what was going on.
So we did have a meeting with Jack Williams and, oh geez, who was head of the
admissions office for so long, not the old guy.
Not Heaton?
No, after Heaton.
Ed Cooper?
Ed Cooper.
Cooper was William's advisor for a while, wasn't he?
Went over, mostly we talked with Cooper about the problem.
Nothing ever came of it, but it all worked out all right.
But that was the early, I don't know how I got involved with black awareness, but somehow I did.
Let's review that a minute.
Given your experience at a few other places and here, do you remember any problems that black students had here?
How did, how were race relations in those early years here?
Well, there were so few blacks that there didn't seem to be, and there were almost none in the College of Business.
I don't, I honestly don't remember ever having a black student in class.
in those days or even in subsequent years.
In my years here until 1980, I really don't remember any incidents, any problems, any difficulties.
I don't either.
I remember being amazed when one of, when the student body president of Black was elected, Fred McClure, that just blew my mind.
I thought that was really, I was impressed with the following.
that generally I thought race relations in Texas were a whole lot better than they were in Louisiana, even though South Louisiana was better than North Louisiana.
And incidentally, an aside, sometime in the last year and a half, there were two programs on NPR, one on how New Orleans handled the school desegregation
or desegregation generally, and how Houston handled it.
And the differences were stark.
And what was the name of our black board member?
There was a doctor.
Anyway, he played apparently a major undercover role in Houston on that deal.
Yes, I think so.
I don't know what was his name.
Because to me, one of the interesting features of the race relations here is we have
a number of youngsters from farms and ranches and other rural settings, as well as urban youngsters, and things seemed to mesh reasonably well.
They did that.
I do seem to recall that one of the early coaches when I came, football coaches, seemed not ever inclined to have a black on the team, but when blacks started
doing good things for the football team.
I think that helped the whole picture, too.
Well, Emery Ballard certainly recruited a number of black players when he- Yes, it was his predecessor, whoever that was.
Alright, what were, how and who and when and why did the business program begin to grow?
I suppose it really began to grow when it was set up as a separate college.
That gave it more prestige.
We sought accreditation from the AACSB and got it.
On the first try?
Yes.
I believe so.
The strong departments, accounting had always been a strong department, even back when it was apparently in agriculture.
Bill Adams, for example, has a College of Agriculture degree in accounting.
My department, there were ten people in it when I stepped down six years later.
Or was it eight years?
It was eight years.
Two four-year terms I had.
What we did was appeal to graduate students, particularly in agricultural finance.
And so we brought in a number of graduate students and said, remember in the early days, if you were a department head, you got a printout showing by professor what the earnings were, by department,
And per faculty member, my department was earning far more money than any others.
We didn't have a big undergraduate group like management did, you know, they had to take all the students.
So we were really, and I was able to get some pretty good money out of Pearson for graduate assistants.
We had at one time half of all the assistantship money in the College of Business.
So we were quite successful.
I hired Pete Rose, kind of a fluke, out of Dallas for a bank, a Federal Reserve bank.
He knew Don Frazier, who's now the head of the Department of Finance, and the two of them made banking a strong subsection of that.
So our department and all the others took off.
Was there ever any kind of,
committee or any other group that made a detailed plan of action for business?
Or was this department by department?
I've never heard of any master plan.
No, there wasn't.
All right.
Describe Pearson as a dean.
How did he operate?
I may have to edit this afterwards.
Okay.
Toward the end, he and I had some problems.
Every Monday we would have a department heads meeting and we'd talk about things but nothing would ever come of it.
It used to drive me nuts.
One of my fellow department heads would always keep bringing stuff up and I kept trying to tell him on the side, don't bring it up because nothing's going to happen.
So that was a
disturbing thing for me.
And I know it galled John when I was made acting head when

he automatically submitted his admission you know his resignation when he was seen and Jarvis Miller came in he submitted his resignation like a cabinet member would to the president of the United States and Jarvis Miller picked it up Jarvis and he had apparently been in the Dominican Republic or something years earlier and gotten at swords points
So John was out.
Well, I was asked to be acting dean.
I don't think that said well with John.
But we did have some
Bad times.
Subsequently, we made up, because we used to party a lot together.
There was a bunch of folks, including John, who was good on a guitar and a banjo.
We'd sit around our pool lot there and play.
Let's see.
Describe Williams as university president from your point of view.
He seemed like the ideal president.
I think the faculty just thought the world of him.
I was impressed with, I think he was just the ideal guy to succeed.
When I'm very biased, I agree with you.
Yeah, I know you do.
Well, I think the whole faculty, anybody who was around.
Why do you think they did?
Well, he was a classy guy, for one thing.
He knew what a real university was about, and he was very affable.
Certainly not military, although his specialty was duels.
But he had a very distinguished marine career in World War II.
Yeah, most of us didn't even know about it, I guess.
And I believe Bob Walker told me that he one time, at William's house,
There were some Marines there, and they cajoled him into putting on his old uniform.
Oh, be darned.
And that nobody else that I've ever talked to ever saw him in the uniform.
No.
And I never heard him talk about his military.
If I'm not mistaken, he was wounded two or three times.
Is that right?
I think he made five landings.
He was decorated and so forth.
Let me share with you Mr.
Rudder's recommendation.
to Fort Albritton and John Lindsay of why they should go get Jack Williams if something ever happened to Rutter.

The heart of it was his experience at Clemson, a separate land grant school in the south, once all male, once compulsory military, once had a corps, once segregated, limited curriculum, off the main highway, 100 miles from the state capitol where the state university was.
that he had been through experiences there just like we had been.
And that he was very, very well regarded in our education as a leader.
Coordinating.
And in the coordinating board.
He also was the University of Tennessee, wasn't he?
He was the number two man in the Tennessee system at the time they went after him.
Yeah.
He had left Austin and gone to Tennessee.
Yeah.
I heard good vibes from Tennessee about him.
So I understand.
And I can't remember that legendary president at Tennessee.
Andy Holt.
Andy Holt.
That Andy Holt was one of his role models.
And the more I know about Andy Holt, the more I can see a little bit of Jack Williams, that Andy was vexed.
Very, very, very skillful, I gather.
He was a consummate politician, and he knew what it was all about.
It was said that you could go to the headwaters of any creek, depending upon how you pronounce it, in Tennessee, and somebody up there would know.
That's what I heard.
Did you have any interaction with Williams that you can pass on to this machine?
No, not really.
Any William stories, anecdotes?
No, I was aware that Dave Maxwell and he used to trade jokes.
What was it that they were into?
Play on words kinds of things.
Puns and all?
Yeah, puns.
No, I really was, you know, at that time,
in the trenches.
I do remember that when I was named acting dean, the press interviewed me as acting dean of the business school.
And I was complimentary of John Pearson, and Jack Williams called me and thanked me for that.
By then, he was having his problems with the board.
Alright, let's jump forward then and get you closer to being in the key role.
Under, you were acting dean for how long?
A year.
A year.
And then went back to the department?
